FFT implementation (updates from Hussain)

  • Challenges FFTW software
  • Buffer area is the half kernel size (different per species)
  • It is faster indeed!

Seed production

The number of seeds per cell is calculated as follow

\[ S_{s,t} = N_{s,i,t} S_{max,s} d_{s,i} \]

where,

\(S_{s,t}\) = max number of seeds \(S_{s,t}\) produced by the trees of species s at time t

\(N_{s,t,}\) = number of trees of that species in that cell

\(S_{max,s}\) = = maximum fecundity per tree and year (user defined values available from table 1b n the supplement from Lischke.2006.

\(d_{s}\) = a light availability function [0,1]. Here we have used the growth limitation factor estimated in LandClim light_rf(t) (name in LandClim manual) GetAvailableLightReductionFactor() (name in LandClim code). This is the main change compared to the TreeMig approach where they used instead a [0,1] value calculated with \(\frac{lai_{s,i}}{lai_{s,max}}\) in relation to the current tree height and maximum tree height.

We discussed about including the seed mast period as a stochastic parameter in the past meeting, but so far it is not included.

Kernel

The kernel per species is defined as before by the species specific effective dispersal distance and max dispersal distance as follow:

\[ P_{seed} =2\begin{cases}0.95 & \text{if}\ dist <= ED_{s} \\e^{-b \cdot dist/MD{s}} & \text{if}\ ED_{s} < dist <= MD{s} \\0 & \text{if}\ dist > MD_{s}6\end{cases} \] In order to apply FFT the kernel is now normalized so the sum of the probabilities will equal 1. This is because we are going to multiply this value by the total number of seeds produce in the focal cell to spread them across the landscape.

Seed dispersal

The exceptions are the same as before: If there is dispersal in one cell (x, y) for one species s it is first defined by:

\[ \text{Dispersal}_{s, x, y}= \begin{cases} \text{TRUE}& \text{if there are no trees in the whole landscape} \\ \text{TRUE} & \text{if } B(BaseSeedProbability)>0\\ \text{TRUE} & \text{if }MD = NA \text{ and } B(MDm1Prob)>0\\ \text{TRUE} & \text{if }MD >= 500 \text{ and } B(MDm1Prob)>0\\ \end{cases} \]

where,

  • BaseSeedProbability= BaseSeedProbabilityuser defined probability, default value = 0.001, it defines if seeds are available, due to background seed rain.
  • MD = MaxDispersalDistance species specific
  • E D= EffectiveDispersalDistance species specific
  • EDm1Prob = EffectiveDm1Probabilityuser defined probability, default value = 0.1
  • MDm1Prob = MaxDm1Probability user defined probability, default value = 0.01

Then the convolution Number of seed X kernel dispersal proportion/probability is calculated providing a map with the number of seeds per cell of each species in that year.

Currently all the cells that have at least 1 species become TRUE for regeneration.

Spatial analysis

  • Here I have run a simulations for single species

  • The landscape is squared (landscape that)1500m x 1500m)

  • There is no slope and the altitude is constant

  • 200 years simulations

  • Initially the landscape is empty except for a initial set of trees in the lower left corner

  • The initial trees are 3 cohorts per cell of 3 different ages (10, 20, 30)

  • The initial densities and biomass varied per species

P. abies

Species characteristics:

  • Age at Maturity= 50

  • Max seed = 96500

  • Dispersal distances:

    • EffectiveDispersalDistance = 70
    • MaxDispersalDistance = 250

Simulation species specific characteristics:

  • Initial biomass per cohort for ages 10, 20 and 30 are 0.01, 0.0105 and 0.012.
  • Initial number of stems per ha 1200 (distributed in the 3 initial cohorts)
  • Altitude 1800m

F. sylvatica

Species characteristics:

  • Age at Maturity= 60

  • Max seed = 29000

  • Dispersal distances:

    • EffectiveDispersalDistance = 30
    • MaxDispersalDistance = -1

Simulation species specific characteristics:

  • Initial biomass per cohort for ages 10, 20 and 30 are 0.003 0.0035 and 0.004
  • Initial number of stems per ha 1600 (distributed in the 3 initial cohorts) (I tried with higher but the trees died)
  • Altitude 1200m

B. pendula

Species characteristics:

  • Age at Maturity= 20

  • Max seeds = 11775000

  • Dispersal distances:

    • EffectiveDispersalDistance = 200
    • MaxDispersalDistance = 700

Simulation species specific characteristics:

  • Initial biomass per cohort for ages 10, 20 and 30 are 0.0122, 0.014 and 0.015
  • Initial number of stems per ha 1600 (distributed in the 3 initial cohorts)
  • Altitude 1000m

P. sylvestris

Species characteristics:

  • Age at Maturity= 30

  • Max seed: 22000

  • Dispersal distances:

    • EffectiveDispersalDistance = 90
    • MaxDispersalDistance = 300

Simulation species specific characteristics:

  • Initial biomass per cohort for ages 10, 20 and 30 are 0.0114, 0.0116 and 0.0118
  • Initial number of stems per ha 1800 (distributed in the 3 initial cohorts per cell)
  • Altitude 900m

Dischma

Conclussions

  • Annual version overestimate regeneration compared with previous version at least in time
  • Spatial patterns look similar in FFT version and decadal version for the 3 selected species
  • Is still unknown exactly why we are having more/faster regeneration than before. My guesses at the moment are:
      1. how the good years for regeneration is estimated in annual, there are more good years for regeneration than before (to be evaluated)
      1. We have more TRUEs than before because of why we are assigning TRUEs compared to the past approach (to be evaluated)
